<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    <a href="/backlog/774-auto-derive-the-a11y-gate-route-set-from-the-11ty-collection/">#774</a> asks whether to
    replace the <strong>hand-maintained</strong> a11y-gate route allowlist
    (<code>tests/a11y/route-allowlist.ts</code>, built in
    <a href="/backlog/770-rendered-site-a11y-gate-axe-lane-route-allowlist-we-docs/">#770</a>) with
    <strong>auto-derivation from the 11ty collection / sitemap</strong>, so every published page is gated without a
    hand-edit. <a href="/backlog/763-gate-ui-best-practices-on-website-changes-rendered-site-a11y/">#763</a>
    deferred this as its Fork-3 alternative; <a href="/backlog/793-remediate-we-docs-a11y-violations-flip-the-rendered-site-gat/">#793</a>
    sharpened it by flipping 9 of 10 routes to build-blocking <code>enforce: true</code> — which
    auto-derivation must not silently un-earn. Two coupled, non-mechanical questions block any code:
    <strong>scope</strong> (what does &ldquo;every published page&rdquo; resolve to?) and <strong>mechanism</strong>
    (there is <em>no</em> sitemap today — <code>/sitemap.xml</code> 404s — so what artifact does the test read?).
</p>

<h2>Recommendation (to ratify in #774)</h2>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Scope — index surfaces + one representative detail page per collection-template.</strong>
        Gate every catalog index (<code>/</code>, <code>/intents/</code>, <code>/blocks/</code>, &hellip;)
        <em>plus</em> one sampled detail page per <code>*-pages.njk</code> template (~26 extra loads). Detail pages
        share a template, so one sample catches the dominant <strong>template-level</strong> regression class — at
        ~1% of the cost of running axe over all 2,129 pages, without the homepage-only blind spot.</li>
    <li><strong>Mechanism — author a <code>sitemap.njk</code> over <code>collections.all</code>; the gate parses it.</strong>
        The 11ty-native, prior-art-blessed path (pa11y-ci's <code>--sitemap</code> is exactly this), and it fills a
        real SEO gap. Beats globbing <code>_site/**</code> (Lighthouse CI's documented nested-dir limitation, and
        <code>eleventy --serve</code> doesn't even write <code>_site</code>) and reconstructing permalinks from
        <code>_data</code> (re-implements logic that lives in 26 templates &rarr; drift).</li>
    <li><strong>Forced invariant (not a fork) — preserve #793's earned enforce posture.</strong> Keep an explicit
        <code>ENFORCED_ROUTES</code> set seeded with the 9 already-enforced routes; newly auto-derived routes enter
        <strong>warn-only</strong> (most-permissive default), promoted per-route as each goes green. &ldquo;Reset all
        to warn&rdquo; is a broken branch (it regresses #793), so this is an invariant, not a choice.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Scope — what &ldquo;every published page&rdquo; should mean</h2>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Option</th><th>What gets gated</th><th>Cost / behaviour</th><th>Verdict</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>A — all pages</strong></td>
            <td>Literally every route (~2,129 <code>index.html</code>, ~790 under <code>/backlog/</code>).</td>
            <td>Matches the item's wording; maximally self-maintaining — but minutes of axe per CI run and scans
                churn-y in-progress detail pages.</td>
            <td>Discouraged extreme — a11y practice explicitly says not to test every page on a large site.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>C — index + per-template sample</strong> <em>(recommended)</em></td>
            <td>All catalog index surfaces + one representative detail page per <code>*-pages.njk</code> collection.</td>
            <td>Bounded (~26 extra loads), self-maintaining as new collections appear; catches shared-template
                regressions (the dominant class).</td>
            <td>The prior-art middle — &ldquo;representative samples across all page types and templates.&rdquo;</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>B — index surfaces only</strong></td>
            <td>The current 10-route class (<code>/intents/</code>, <code>/blocks/</code>, &hellip;), auto-discovered.</td>
            <td>Fast and stable, but no detail page is ever gated.</td>
            <td>The &ldquo;homepage-only misses issues&rdquo; anti-pattern; narrower than &ldquo;every page.&rdquo;</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h2>Mechanism — what artifact the gate reads</h2>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>How it works</th><th>Couples the gate to&hellip;</th><th>Fit</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Author <code>sitemap.njk</code>, parse it</strong> <em>(recommended)</em></td>
            <td>A template iterates <code>collections.all</code> → <code>/sitemap.xml</code>; the Playwright gate
                fetches and parses it (same origin it already hits).</td>
            <td>A published, standard artifact (sitemaps.org) — 11ty's own page knowledge.</td>
            <td>Best — pa11y-ci's <code>--sitemap</code> is exactly this; doubles as the missing SEO sitemap.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Glob <code>_site/**/index.html</code></td>
            <td>Enumerate built HTML on disk after a full build.</td>
            <td>The build output dir (and a full build must run first).</td>
            <td>Weak — <code>eleventy --serve</code> serves from memory (no <code>_site</code>), and LHCI's
                <code>staticDistDir</code> shows the nested-dir glob is fiddly (issue&nbsp;#95: root-only).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Reconstruct from <code>_data</code></td>
            <td>Import the JSON collections, rebuild URLs from the permalink patterns.</td>
            <td>26 templates' permalink logic, re-implemented in the test.</td>
            <td>Brittle — duplicates logic that lives in the templates; drifts when a permalink changes.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h2>Why one detail page per template suffices</h2>
<p>
    Every detail page is generated by a single paginating template over a <code>_data</code> collection —
    <code>src/intent-pages.njk</code> (<code>permalink: "intents/{{ intent.id }}/"</code>) renders <em>all</em>
    intents, <code>block-pages.njk</code> all blocks, and so on across 26 templates. So an axe violation on a detail
    page is almost always a <strong>template</strong> bug shared by every page of that type, which one sampled page
    catches; the residual (a content-specific violation in one item's markdown) is rare and lower-value to gate.
    That is the structural reason scope-C gives ~95% of scope-A's coverage at ~1% of its cost.
</p>

<h2>Classification</h2>
<p>
    A <strong>devtools quality gate</strong> (kin to <code>check:standards</code> and the existing a11y lane) — the
    same classification <a href="/backlog/763-gate-ui-best-practices-on-website-changes-rendered-site-a11y/">#763</a>
    recorded. Zero consumer lock-in; <strong>no protocol minted</strong> (a sitemap is the sitemaps.org artifact and
    axe <em>is</em> the WCAG engine — both consumed, not re-specified). Mirrored <strong>per-repo</strong>: FUI's gate
    (<a href="/backlog/771-mirror-the-rendered-site-a11y-gate-into-frontier-ui-3001/">#771</a>) would derive from its
    own sitemap, following the duplicated-dev-panel pattern.
</p>

